\section{Dataset and Sampling}\label{sec:meth:data}

CUAD~\cite{hendrycks2021cuad} is the evaluation corpus (see Table~\ref{tab:cuad-stats}
for statistics). We restrict to 81 contracts $>$100{,}000 characters because
long-context performance is the regime where decomposition is hypothesised to add
value and approximates the operational distribution of CLM platforms surveyed in
Section~\ref{sec:lit:clm}. The 81-contract subset yields
$81 \times 41 = 3{,}321$ raw (contract, category) pairs per evaluation pass.

\paragraph{Sampling strategy.}\label{sec:meth:sampling}\label{sec:sampling}
A \texttt{neg\_ratio=0.7} sampler produces a 30\%/70\% positive/negative split per
run, mirroring CUAD's natural class prior at the (contract, category) level. Two
design considerations motivate this choice. First, ContractEval evaluates 4{,}128
instances drawn at the natural distribution, and matching that protocol enables direct
comparability with the closest empirical predecessor~\cite{liu2025contracteval}.
Second, prior work that resamples to inflated positive ratios suppresses the
false-positive denominator and masks over-extraction (Eq.~\ref{eq:overextract}),
detaching the evaluation distribution from any deployable distribution. The natural
prior preserves both laziness (Eq.~\ref{eq:laziness}) and over-extraction
(Eq.~\ref{eq:overextract}) as observable quantities. Sampling is seeded
(\texttt{seed=42}) so the same (contract, category) pairs are evaluated across all
configurations, making every statistical test paired at the instance level.
Each run yields $\approx\!2{,}999$ predictions; 1{,}297 of 164{,}941 total
($0.79\%$) were excluded for malformed classification tokens.

\paragraph{Prevalence tiers.}
The 41 CUAD categories are partitioned into three tiers --- \emph{common},
\emph{moderate}, \emph{rare} --- by natural positive rate in the 81-contract subset.
Tier cutpoints are fixed before any model is run.

